<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What Markdown syntax does this converter support?", answer: "The converter handles headings (h1 through h6), bold, italic, bold+italic, strikethrough, inline code, fenced code blocks with language hints, links, images, unordered and ordered lists, blockquotes, horizontal rules, tables, and paragraphs. It covers the vast majority of CommonMark and GitHub Flavored Markdown features." },
  { question: "Is the conversion done on a server?", answer: "No. The Markdown is parsed and converted to HTML entirely in your browser using JavaScript. Nothing is sent to any server. You can disconnect from the internet and the converter continues to work." },
  { question: "Can I use the generated HTML in my website?", answer: "Yes. The output is clean, semantic HTML that you can copy and paste into any web page, email template, CMS, or static site generator. The HTML uses standard tags like p, h1-h6, strong, em, ul, ol, pre, code, blockquote, and table." },
  { question: "Does the converter sanitize the HTML output?", answer: "The converter escapes special HTML characters in your Markdown input, which prevents accidental injection of raw HTML tags. If your Markdown source contains angle brackets or ampersands, they appear as literal characters in the output rather than being interpreted as HTML." },
  { question: "How are code blocks handled?", answer: "Fenced code blocks (triple backticks) are wrapped in pre and code tags. If you specify a language after the opening backticks, a language class is added to the code element for syntax highlighting compatibility with libraries like Prism.js or Highlight.js." }
]) %>

<%= calculator_schema(
  name: "Markdown to HTML Converter",
  description: "Convert Markdown syntax to clean, semantic HTML with live preview.",
  url: everyday_markdown_to_html_url,
  category: "UtilityApplication"
) %>

<%# Breadcrumbs %>
